Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["KnoodleIdentify", "ObjectName",ExpressionUUID->"1e0d8f61-1266-435e-ad09-9e139c1119c7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell["   ", "ModInfo",ExpressionUUID->"3f2b9626-1065-4a40-9244-370228549cde"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"KnoodleIdentify", "[", 
   StyleBox["input", "TI"], "]"}]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "6e5d7f07-3d15-41d3-b26a-65a541313b14"],
 "\[LineSeparator]identifies the knot type of a knot diagram by looking it up \
in Knoodle's knot lookup table (KLUT)."
}], "Usage",ExpressionUUID->"4ffcf781-8254-45e8-b322-24afaaad0598"],

Cell["\<\
KnoodleIdentify returns an Association from each identified prime summand, a \
KnotSymbol[c, i, alternating, coset], to its integer multiplicity. A connect \
sum of several prime knots gives one entry per distinct prime factor, with \
the factor's multiplicity as the value. The unknot gives <||>, the empty \
association: an unknot summand is the identity element for connect sum, so it \
is simply omitted.\
\>", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"760e953a-2800-4a9e-963c-4af2acb29932"],

Cell["\<\
input accepts the same representations as KnoodleDraw. The lookup is \
self-contained: it decomposes and simplifies internally, so input need not be \
simplified first.\
\>", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"f31d8fbc-8bb4-4539-91c2-72103a734830"],

Cell["\<\
A summand with more crossings than the lookup table covers comes back as \
Unidentified[n, pd] -> multiplicity, where pd is the summand's own signed PD \
code, for offline analysis. A summand inside the table's range that still \
fails to resolve comes back as NotFound[n, pd] -> multiplicity instead.\
\>", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"ca2e9648-c37a-40f9-8800-0764add4e811"],

Cell["\<\
KnoodleIdentify only identifies knots. A genuine link (more than one \
component) fails with $Failed and a KnoodleIdentify::link message; apply \
KnoodleSimplify with \"Unite\" -> True first if the components should be \
treated as connect-summed into a single knot.\
\>", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"f25f88e9-0b04-4531-b0e4-23eae6c39f07"],

Cell["\<\
3D geometry is projected straight down the z axis before identification. A \
highly symmetric curve can produce a degenerate projection and fail; rotate \
such a curve into general position first (e.g. with RotationTransform).\
\>", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"187e7e53-7afc-4429-9301-a30cbcddbee4"],

Cell["The following options can be given:", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"03eea07d-1085-403b-a0e8-21e6bdd3ef14"],

Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {Cell["      ", "ModInfo",ExpressionUUID->
     "e5b0b2f2-30b0-4530-a9a9-a73a48c678f2"], "\"\<MaxCrossings\>\"", 
    "Automatic", Cell["\<\
restrict the lookup to subtables with at most this many crossings (3 to 13); \
Automatic is the table's full range. Knots above a restricted range come back \
as NotFound.\
\>", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->"79c9b5c3-d682-43f3-ac70-0e6a48b54e54"]}
  }]], "3ColumnTableMod",ExpressionUUID->"a00ce6e9-1e9f-49e5-be16-\
3debbbeb3a36"]
}, Open  ]],

